Yes, this is due to how templates are compiled and linked in C++. Template classes are not actual classes, but rather blueprints for creating classes. As a result, the actual code for the template class is not generated until you instantiate it with a specific type.

In your case, when you declare `static AutoRegisterTemplate<ModuleClassA> file_local_var` in a .cpp file, the compiler doesn't know which types `AutoRegisterTemplate` will be used with, so it doesn't generate any code for it. The linker then sees that there are no references to any symbols defined in the my_module_a.cpp file and decides to optimize it away.

To avoid this, you can force the instantiation of the `AutoRegisterTemplate` class by explicitly creating an instance of it for each module class you want to register. One way to do this is to create a function template that takes a `ModuleClass` type and creates a static instance of `AutoRegisterTemplate` for it. For example:

```
template <typename ModuleClass>
void registerModule() {
    static AutoRegisterTemplate<ModuleClass> registrar;
}

// in my_module_a.cpp
registerModule<ModuleClassA>();
```

This will ensure that there is at least one instance of `AutoRegisterTemplate<ModuleClass>` created for each module class, which will in turn call the constructor and add the `ModuleClass::Register` function pointer to the `all_register_funcs` map.

