I apologize for the confusion. You are correct that defining `registerModule<ModuleClassA>();` in the .cpp file will not work, as it will cause a redefinition error when the linker tries to link the object files.

To avoid the redefinition error, you can declare the `registerModule()` function template in a header file and define it in a single .cpp file. This way, the `registerModule()` function template is declared in all translation units that include the header file, but only defined once in the .cpp file, so there is no redefinition error.

Here's an example of how you could modify the code:

```
// register_module.h
#pragma once

template <typename ModuleClass>
void registerModule();

// my_module_a.cpp
#include "register_module.h"
#include "module_class_a.h"

template <>
void registerModule<ModuleClassA>() {
    static AutoRegisterTemplate<ModuleClassA> registrar;
}

// my_module_b.cpp
#include "register_module.h"
#include "module_class_b.h"

template <>
void registerModule<ModuleClassB>() {
    static AutoRegisterTemplate<ModuleClassB> registrar;
}
```

In the example above, `registerModule()` is declared in the `register_module.h` header file, and the template specialization for each module class is defined in the corresponding .cpp files. This way, every module that includes the `register_module.h` header file will have access to the `registerModule()` function template, which can be used to register the module's `ModuleClass::Register` function.
